To implement a dictionary using a binary search tree (BST) in C++, we need to define a `Node` structure to represent each entry in the BST, and then create a `Dictionary` class that manages the BST operations.

Here's a step-by-step breakdown of the program:

---

### **Step 1: Define the Node Structure**
Each node in the BST will store a word and its definition, along with pointers to left and right children.

```cpp
struct Node {
    std::string word;
    std::string definition;
    Node* left;
    Node* right;
    Node(std::string w, std::string d) : word(w), definition(d), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}
};
```

---

### **Step 2: Define the Dictionary Class**
The `Dictionary` class will manage the BST operations, including insertion, lookup, deletion, and printing.

```cpp
class Dictionary {
private:
    Node* root;
    void insert(Node* &node, std::string word, std::string definition);
    Node* search(Node* node, std::string word);
    void deleteNode(Node* &node, std::string word);
    void printInOrder(Node* node);
    void printPostOrder(Node* node);
    void printPreOrder(Node* node);

public:
    Dictionary();
    void insertWord(std::string word, std::string definition);
    std::string lookupWord(std::string word);
    void deleteWord(std::string word);
    void printDictionary();
};
```

---

### **Step 3: Implement BST Operations**
Implement the `insert`, `search`, `delete`, and `print` methods.

```cpp
void Dictionary::insert(Node* &node, std::string word, std::string definition) {
    if (node == nullptr) {
        node = new Node(word, definition);
        return;
    }

    if (word < node->word) {
        insert(node->left, word, definition);
    } else {
        insert(node->right, word, definition);
    }
}

Node* Dictionary::search(Node* node, std::string word) {
    if (node == nullptr || node->word == word) {
        return node;
    }

    if (word < node->word) {
        return search(node->left, word);
    } else {
        return search(node->right, word);
    }
}

void Dictionary::deleteNode(Node* &node, std::string word) {
    if (node == nullptr) {
        return;
    }

    if (word < node->word) {
        deleteNode(node->left, word);
    } else if (word > node->word) {
        deleteNode(node->right, word);
    } else {
        // Node found, delete it
        if (node->left == nullptr) {
            Node* temp = node->right;
            delete node;
            node = temp;
        } else if (node->right == nullptr) {
            Node* temp = node->left;
            delete node;
            node = temp;
        } else {
            // Node has two children: find the in-order successor
            Node* temp = node->right;
            while (temp->left != nullptr) {
                temp = temp->left;
            }

            // Copy the in-order successor's value to current node
            node->word = temp->word;
            node->definition = temp->definition;

            // Delete the in-order successor
            deleteNode(node->right, temp->word);
        }
    }
}

void Dictionary::printInOrder(Node* node) {
    if (node != nullptr) {
        printInOrder(node->left);
        std::cout << node->word << ": " << node->definition << std::endl;
        printInOrder(node->right);
    }
}

void Dictionary::printPostOrder(Node* node) {
    if (node != nullptr) {
        printPostOrder(node->left);
        printPostOrder(node->right);
        std::cout << node->word << ": " << node->definition << std::endl;
    }
}

void Dictionary::printPreOrder(Node* node) {
    if (node != nullptr) {
        std::cout << node->word << ": " << node->definition << std::endl;
        printPreOrder(node->left);
        printPreOrder(node->right);
    }
}
```

---

### **Step 4: Main Function**
The main function will interact with the user, allowing them to insert words, look them up, delete them, and print the dictionary.

```cpp
int main() {
    Dictionary dict;

    std::string word, definition;
    int choice;

    while (true) {
        std::cout << "Dictionary Menu:\n";
        std::cout << "1. Insert Word\n";
        std::cout << "2. Lookup Word\n";
        std::cout << "3. Delete Word\n";
        std::cout << "4. Print Dictionary\n";
        std::cout << "5. Exit\n";
        std::cout << "Enter your choice: ";

        std::cin >> choice;

        switch (choice) {
            case 1:
                std::cout << "Enter word: ";
                std::cin >> word;
                std::cout << "Enter definition: ";
                std::cin >> definition;
                dict.insertWord(word, definition);
                break;
            case 2:
                std::cout << "Enter word to look up: ";
                std::cin >> word;
                std::string result = dict.lookupWord(word);
                if (result.empty()) {
                    std::cout << "Word not found.\n";
                } else {
                    std::cout << "Definition: " << result << std::endl;
                }
                break;
            case 3:
                std::cout << "Enter word to delete: ";
                std::cin >> word;
                dict.deleteWord(word);
                break;
            case 4:
                dict.printDictionary();
                break;
            case 5:
                std::cout << "Exiting the dictionary.\n";
                return 0;
            default:
                std::cout << "Invalid choice. Please try again.\n";
        }
    }

    return 0;
}
```

---

### **Step 5: Compile and Run**
Compile the program with the following command:
```bash
g++ dictionary.cpp -o dictionary
```

Run the program:
```bash
./dictionary
```

